<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "Why do different woods weigh different amounts?", answer: "Wood density varies with species because of differences in cell structure, cell wall thickness, and extractives. Dense tropical hardwoods like ipe and purpleheart can weigh more than twice as much as light softwoods like western red cedar or eastern white pine for the same volume. Growth rate, portion of heartwood versus sapwood, and the natural oils or silica content also influence weight. Species density is usually reported at 12 percent moisture content, which is the typical interior equilibrium value." },
  { question: "How does moisture content affect weight?", answer: "Freshly cut or green lumber can weigh 40 to 60 percent more than the same board at 8 percent moisture content. As wood dries, water evaporates first from the cell cavities and then from the cell walls, reducing weight substantially. Kiln-dried lumber sold for interior woodworking is usually at 6 to 8 percent moisture content. Construction lumber stamped KD or S-DRY is closer to 15 to 19 percent. Wet framing lumber can be noticeably heavier to handle on the job site." },
  { question: "What's the heaviest hardwood?", answer: "Among commercially available hardwoods, lignum vitae is the densest, with a specific gravity above 1.2, meaning it sinks in water. Ipe, cumaru, santos mahogany, and ebony are all very heavy as well, generally in the 65 to 75 pounds per cubic foot range. Purpleheart, bloodwood, and bubinga are also notably heavy. These tropical species are popular for decking, flooring, tool handles, and outdoor furniture because their density contributes to durability and rot resistance." },
  { question: "How do I convert between lb/ft³ and kg/m³?", answer: "Multiply pounds per cubic foot by 16.0185 to get kilograms per cubic meter. Divide kilograms per cubic meter by 16.0185 to go the other direction. For example, red oak at 44 lb/ft³ is approximately 705 kg/m³. This calculator displays both units automatically so there is no need to convert by hand." },
  { question: "How much does a 4x8 sheet of plywood weigh?", answer: "A full 4 by 8 foot sheet of plywood weight depends on thickness and species. A half-inch sheet of softwood plywood typically weighs around 40 pounds, three-quarter inch softwood plywood is around 60 pounds, and hardwood plywood such as birch tends to be about 15 to 20 percent heavier than softwood at the same thickness. Medium-density fiberboard at three-quarter inch thickness weighs about 95 pounds per sheet, noticeably heavier than plywood." }
]) %>

