    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How Wood Weight Is Calculated</h2>
      <p>
        This calculator finds the volume of a board in cubic feet by multiplying thickness, width, and length and dividing by 1728 to convert cubic inches to cubic feet. Length is accepted in feet and converted internally. That volume is then multiplied by the species density in pounds per cubic foot to produce weight per piece. Multiplying by the quantity provides the total weight and total volume, with automatic conversion to kilograms and cubic meters. The density values used are averages at 12 percent moisture content, which is typical for kiln-dried interior lumber.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Density vs Specific Gravity</h2>
      <p>
        Wood science literature often lists density as specific gravity, which is the ratio of oven dry weight to the weight of an equal volume of water. Specific gravity is dimensionless and makes direct species comparisons easy. Density in pounds per cubic foot or kilograms per cubic meter is more useful for practical calculations because it is tied to real weight units. A specific gravity of 0.65 for red oak corresponds to roughly 44 pounds per cubic foot at 12 percent moisture content, which is the value this calculator uses.
      </p>

      <h2>Why Species Matters</h2>
      <p>
        Choosing the right species for a project involves more than appearance. Weight affects shipping costs, how a piece of furniture feels in use, how much tools will have to lift when cutting long boards, and how heavily a structure must be built to support a load. A solid oak tabletop feels reassuringly substantial, while a pine version of the same table is easier to move but less imposing. For hand-carried boards on a job site, knowing the weight in advance helps plan manpower and prevents injuries.
      </p>

      <h2>Moisture Content and Weight</h2>
      <p>
        The values here assume normal kiln-dried lumber around 12 percent moisture. Green or wet lumber can weigh substantially more, sometimes 40 to 60 percent more than the same board after drying. If you are estimating weight for freshly milled lumber, expect to add significant weight for the water still in the cells. Conversely, very dry lumber at 6 to 8 percent can weigh slightly less than the table values. For most practical estimates, 12 percent is the right reference point.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>Why do different woods weigh different amounts?</h3>
      <p>
        Density varies with cell structure and wall thickness. Dense tropical hardwoods like ipe weigh more than twice as much as lightweight softwoods like cedar for the same volume.
      </p>

      <h3>How does moisture content affect weight?</h3>
      <p>
        Green lumber can weigh 40 to 60 percent more than kiln-dried lumber of the same species and size because the cells still contain free water.
      </p>

      <h3>What's the heaviest hardwood?</h3>
      <p>
        Lignum vitae is the densest commercial hardwood, heavy enough to sink in water. Ipe, ebony, santos mahogany, and purpleheart are also extremely heavy.
      </p>

      <h3>How do I convert between lb/ft³ and kg/m³?</h3>
      <p>
        Multiply pounds per cubic foot by 16.0185 to get kilograms per cubic meter. This calculator displays both units automatically.
      </p>

      <h3>How much does a 4x8 sheet of plywood weigh?</h3>
      <p>
        A half-inch softwood sheet is around 40 pounds, three-quarter inch softwood is around 60 pounds, and three-quarter inch MDF is closer to 95 pounds.
      </p>

